Get the sub gffs

stopifnot(names(gff3s) == names(ID.list))
sgff3 <- mcmapply(extractFromGff3UsingGeneIDs,gff3s,ID.list,mc.cores=6L)

cov.idt <- mclapply(sgff3,function(gff){
  t(apply(getGffAttribute(gff[gff$type=="mRNA",],c("coverage","identity")),1,as.numeric))
},mc.cores=6L)

This is pretty cool

  1. Potrs and Potra are very similar and some genes seem to be extremely conserved, otherwise the peaks peak around 98-99%

  2. Potri aligned to Potra or Potrs show very similar curves (first and last), which is a good validation

  3. Potra and Potrs and aligned to Potri show a different story, which might be interesting. Potra has less identity to Potri than Potrs has. Either this is due to the lower quality (or higher hererozygousity) of the Potra assembly or it starts to show the fact that Potri and Potrs are closer environmentally and that Potra and Potrs have started to drift away, influenced by the continental environment

plot.multidensity(lapply(cov.idt,function(m){m[,2]}),xlab="identity",lwd=2,xlim=c(80,100))

Most of the path have a full coverage

par(mar=c(7.1,4.1,0.1,0.1))
boxplot(lapply(cov.idt,function(m){m[,1]}),ylim=c(80,100),las=2)

par(mar=mar)

2.2 Graphs

Create a list of edges

edges.list <- lapply(res,"[",c(9,18))
edges.list <- lapply(edges.list,function(edges){
  cbind(gsub("ID=|;.*","",edges[,1]),
        gsub(".*Name=|\\.0$","",edges[,2]))})

Report on the number of links and the number of missing

stats <- do.call(rbind,lapply(edges.list,function(edges){
  tab <- table(table(edges[,2]))
  mult <- rep(as.integer(names(tab[-c(1,length(tab))])),tab[-c(1,length(tab))])
  c(total=nrow(edges),
    gene=length(unique(edges[,1])),
    gene.mapped=length(unique(edges[,2]))-1,
    gene.unique.mapped=sum(table(edges[,2])==1),
    gene.multi=sum(table(edges[,2])>1) - 1,
    gene.multi.mean=mean(mult),
    gene.multi.median=median(mult),
    gene.multi.sd=sd(mult),
    gene.multi.min=min(mult),
    gene.multi.max=max(mult),
    gene.missed=sum(edges[,2]==".")
    )
}))

2.3 Intersects

This all looks good, lets count the number of clusters and how many species are involved in each

cluster.members.mat <- do.call(rbind,lapply(lapply(lapply(split(get.vertex.attribute(graph = graf,name="name"),
                                         clusters(graf)$membership),substr,1,5),
                            factor,levels=c("Potra","Potri","Potrs")),table))

How does this look as a venn diagram?

plot.new()
grid.draw(venn.diagram(
  lapply(1:3,function(i,dat){which(dat[,i])},cluster.members.mat > 0),
  filename=NULL,
  col=pal[1:3],
  category.names = colnames(cluster.members.mat)
))

2.6 Venn Diagram

We obtain from every species their synthetic transcript ID set.

Potra.st <- sub("\\.0$","",names(readDNAStringSet("/mnt/picea/storage/reference/Populus-tremula/v1.0/fasta/Potra01-synthetic-transcripts.fa")))
Potri.st <- sub("\\.0$","",names(readDNAStringSet("/mnt/picea/storage/reference/Populus-trichocarpa/v3.0/fasta/Potri03-synthetic-transcripts.fa")))
Potrs.st <- sub("\\.0$","",names(readDNAStringSet("/mnt/picea/storage/reference/Populus-tremuloides/v1.0/fasta/Potrs01-synthetic-transcripts.fa")))

The total number of genes is:

all.genes <- length(c(Potra.st,Potri.st,Potrs.st))
sprintf("The three species have a total of %s genes",all.genes)
## [1] "The three species have a total of 115585 genes"

Which is split into the following

n1 <- sum(!Potra.st %in% unlist(all.edges))
n2 <- sum(!Potri.st %in% unlist(all.edges))
n3 <- sum(!Potrs.st %in% unlist(all.edges))
n12 <- sum(unlist(cluster.members.mat[cluster.members.mat[,"Potrs"] == 0,c("Potra","Potri")]))
n23 <- sum(unlist(cluster.members.mat[cluster.members.mat[,"Potra"] == 0,c("Potri","Potrs")]))
n13 <- sum(unlist(cluster.members.mat[cluster.members.mat[,"Potri"] == 0,c("Potra","Potrs")]))
n123 <- sum(unlist(cluster.members.mat[rowSums(cluster.members.mat == 0) == 0,]))

Validate

vals <- c(n1,n2,n3,n12,n23,n13,n123)
stopifnot(sum(vals) == all.genes)

Convert into percentage

vals <- round(vals / all.genes * 1000,digits=0)

Plot

The represented values are in thousandth (tenth of percentage). Reason is simply that VennDiagram does not deal so well with non integers.

plot.new()
grid.draw(
  draw.triple.venn(
  area1=vals[1] + vals[4] + vals[6] + vals[7],
  area2=vals[2] + vals[4] + vals[5] + vals[7],
  area3=vals[3] + vals[5] + vals[6] + vals[7],
  n12=vals[4] + vals[7],
  n23=vals[5] + vals[7],
  n13=vals[6] + vals[7],
  n123=vals[7],
  col=pal[1:3],
  category = colnames(cluster.members.mat),
  ind=FALSE,euler.d=FALSE,scale=FALSE
))

The same with the actual values

plot.new()
grid.draw(
